result.execSummary:
The defendant Timothy George Marincel was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Timothy George Marincel is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Timothy George Marincel was found guilty of Possession of synthetic cannabinoid 1st offense, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(em).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Timothy George Marincel in court with attorney Kasey Grams.  Defendant Timothy George Marincel in custody.  Jon D. Seifert appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Counsel rec'd revocation packet, no corrections.  State filed new charge in 15CM52.  Court advised defendant of charge; inquires of violation date. State moves to amend 15CM52 to reflect between 3-01-2014 - 03-31-2104.  No objection by defendant.  Court amends violation dates as requested.  Court advised defendant of charge as amended/max. penalties.  Defendant pleads guilty.  Plea Colloquy.  Court finds defendant's waiver of his constitutional rights and plea done K&V, accepts plea and finds defendant guilty.  State recommends time served on revocation and any sentence court imposes on new charge run concurrent with revocation sentence.  Court sentences defendant on revocation case to 100 days in the PCJ with credit for 75 days served; enter judgment for unpaid court obligations.  In 15CM52, withhold sentence and place on 2 yrs. probation with conditions:  provide DNA sample; pay court costs w/in 1st year of probation; waive DNA surcharge; complete sex offender evaluation and comply with all treatment and recommendations; appeal rights.
